I tried that code once. It is true that it is not accurate and there were many mistaken matches also. If you will find the same thing in the same image, you can take the pixel values of the template then you can search those pixel values on the image. The fitted one will be your template. The way learning pixel values of an image is that:

  

      for(int i = 0; i &lt; img.rows; i++)
    {
        for(int j = 0; j &lt; img.cols; j++)
        {
            Vec3b bgr_values = img.at&lt;Vec3b&gt;(i, j);
            //This bgr_values will give you the code of each pixel
        }
    }

Template matching is similar to one-shot learning which will never work accurately because you are using only one image as reference. If you only look for a specific template you can develop an algorithm according to that object using basic morphological opencv functions. If you need accurate results maybe you need to use some deep learning algorithms. I can advise you YOLO which is easy to use and you can look at [here][1]


  [1]: https://www.learnopencv.com/training-yolov3-deep-learning-based-custom-object-detector/

